segments.text: We need to stop trying to pay people to do nothing, which is what we're doing, pay people to do nothing.
And we sometimes can't get enough people to work.
And I think we've got to release a...
some sort of mentality developed that the government's supposed to take care of everybody that doesn't want to work.
And I don't say that there aren't some people that need it, and there are, but I think we've gone overboard the other way.
I was at a meeting yesterday where we were discussing CETA.
They poured money down a rat hole.
And very little good has come out of it.
They tried to take all these things that they targeted groups and put them all in one act.
Comprehensive Education Training Act.
It's a disaster.
They put people in training and pay them more while they're in training than they can make after they get through training.
You think they want to work then?
We pay them with no withholding, no income tax.
Pay their transportation, pay their child care, and all that.
Then they go to work at a job with minimum wage.
And they already get minimum wage, plus a tax credit.
So we've got a lot of strange values.
I think the role of the woman in our society has changed completely, and for the good.
And when we were even thinking at the end of World War II, how would we ever get the manpower to fight Russia?
The only way we would get it
The only other source we had was women.
That's the only other source.
So I think they're going to be important in many, many ways.
If they only replace men in civilian jobs so that men can go fight what they have to fight.
I hope we don't.
I think we ought to be prepared to do that.
this universal military training would give us a backlog of reservoir to draw from in case we needed it, with some training.
And I certainly hope we don't have to fight a war.
Thanks a lot for the interview.
